        <h2>MySQL Fundamentals</h2>

        <h3>Core Concepts</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>ACID Properties:</strong> Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability</li>
            <li><strong>Storage Engines:</strong> InnoDB (default, ACID-compliant), MyISAM (no transactions)</li>
            <li><strong>Data Types:</strong> INT, VARCHAR, TEXT, DATETIME, TIMESTAMP, JSON, BLOB</li>
            <li><strong>Indexes:</strong>
                <pre>-- B-Tree index (default)
CREATE INDEX idx_cve_id ON vulnerabilities(cve_id);

-- Composite index
CREATE INDEX idx_severity_status ON vulnerabilities(severity, status);

-- Full-text search
CREATE FULLTEXT INDEX idx_description ON vulnerabilities(description);

-- Check index usage
EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM vulnerabilities WHERE cve_id = 'CVE-2024-1234';</pre>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Query Optimization</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>EXPLAIN Analysis:</strong>
                <pre>EXPLAIN SELECT v.*, a.name 
FROM vulnerabilities v
JOIN assets a ON v.asset_id = a.id
WHERE v.severity = 'CRITICAL';</pre>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Index Strategies:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Index foreign keys</li>
                    <li>Index columns used in WHERE, ORDER BY, GROUP BY</li>
                    <li>Use covering indexes when possible</li>
                    <li>Avoid over-indexing (slows INSERT/UPDATE)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Query Best Practices:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use LIMIT for pagination</li>
                    <li>Avoid SELECT * (specify columns)</li>
                    <li>Use JOIN instead of subqueries when possible</li>
                    <li>Batch INSERT operations</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Advanced Features</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Transactions:</strong>
                <pre>START TRANSACTION;

UPDATE vulnerabilities SET status = 'resolved' WHERE id = 123;
INSERT INTO audit_log (action, vulnerability_id) VALUES ('resolved', 123);

COMMIT;  -- or ROLLBACK on error</pre>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Stored Procedures:</strong>
                <pre>DELIMITER//

CREATE PROCEDURE GetCriticalVulnerabilities()
BEGIN
    SELECT * FROM vulnerabilities 
    WHERE severity = 'CRITICAL' 
    AND status = 'open';
END //

DELIMITER;</pre>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Triggers:</strong>
                <pre>CREATE TRIGGER update_timestamp
BEFORE UPDATE ON vulnerabilities
FOR EACH ROW
SET NEW.updated_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;</pre>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Views:</strong>
                <pre>CREATE VIEW critical_open_vulns AS
SELECT v.*, a.name as asset_name
FROM vulnerabilities v
JOIN assets a ON v.asset_id = a.id
WHERE v.severity = 'CRITICAL' AND v.status = 'open';</pre>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>SingleStore (MemSQL)</h2>

        <h3>Key Features</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Distributed SQL Database:</strong> MySQL wire protocol compatible</li>
            <li><strong>RowStore vs ColumnStore:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>RowStore: OLTP workloads, fast writes, point queries</li>
                    <li>ColumnStore: OLAP workloads, analytics, aggregations</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>In-Memory Performance:</strong> Caching and lock-free data structures</li>
            <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Horizontal scaling with distributed partitions</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>When to Use SingleStore</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Real-time analytics on large datasets</li>
            <li>High-velocity data ingestion (150+ security tools)</li>
            <li>Complex aggregations across billions of vulnerability records</li>
            <li>Mixed OLTP and OLAP workloads</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Database Design for Vulnerability Management</h2>

        <h3>Schema Example</h3>
        <pre>-- Assets table
CREATE TABLE assets (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    type ENUM('server', 'application', 'network', 'container'),
    ip_address VARCHAR(45),
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    INDEX idx_type (type)
);

-- Vulnerabilities table
CREATE TABLE vulnerabilities (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    cve_id VARCHAR(20) UNIQUE,
    asset_id INT,
    severity ENUM('LOW', 'MEDIUM', 'HIGH', 'CRITICAL'),
    status ENUM('open', 'in_progress', 'resolved', 'false_positive'),
    cvss_score DECIMAL(3,1),
    description TEXT,
    source_tool VARCHAR(100),
    discovered_at TIMESTAMP,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    FOREIGN KEY (asset_id) REFERENCES assets(id),
    INDEX idx_severity_status (severity, status),
    INDEX idx_cve_id (cve_id),
    INDEX idx_source (source_tool),
    FULLTEXT idx_description (description)
);

-- Remediation actions
CREATE TABLE remediation_actions (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
   vulnerability_id INT,
    action_type ENUM('patch', 'mitigate', 'accept_risk'),
    assigned_to VARCHAR(100),
    due_date DATE,
    completed_at TIMESTAMP NULL,
    FOREIGN KEY (vulnerability_id) REFERENCES vulnerabilities(id)
);</pre>

        <h3>Normalization</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>1NF:</strong> Atomic values, no repeating groups</li>
            <li><strong>2NF:</strong> No partial dependencies</li>
            <li><strong>3NF:</strong> No transitive dependencies</li>
            <li><strong>Denormalization:</strong> When to break rules for performance (read-heavy systems)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Performance & Scaling</h2>

        <h3>Partitioning</h3>
        <pre>-- Partition by date range
CREATE TABLE vulnerability_history (
    id INT,
    discovery_date DATE,
    ...
)
PARTITION BY RANGE (YEAR(discovery_date)) (
    PARTITION p2023 VALUES LESS THAN (2024),
    PARTITION p2024 VALUES LESS THAN (2025),
    PARTITION p2025 VALUES LESS THAN (2026)
);</pre>

        <h3>Replication</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Master-Slave:</strong> Read replicas for scaling reads</li>
            <li><strong>Master-Master:</strong> Multi-region writes</li>
            <li><strong>Group Replication:</strong> Multi-master with conflict resolution</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Caching Strategies</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Query result caching (Redis, Memcached)</li>
            <li>Application-level caching</li>
            <li>MySQL query cache (deprecated in MySQL 8.0)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Big Data Analytics Systems</h2>

        <h3>Comparison (Know the Basics)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>BigQuery:</strong> Google Cloud serverless data warehouse, SQL-based, columnar storage</li>
            <li><strong>Redshift:</strong> AWS data warehouse, Postgres-based, columnar</li>
            <li><strong>Snowflake:</strong> Cloud data platform, multi-cloud, separation of storage/compute</li>
            <li><strong>Databricks:</strong> Lakehouse platform, Spark-based, unified analytics</li>
            <li><strong>SingleStore:</strong> Real-time analytics, MySQL-compatible, in-memory</li>
        </ul>

